# Cursor Rules for skill-trust

## Project Overview
skill-trust is a transparency verifier for Agent Skills. It parses SKILL.md trust declarations and compares them against actual code behavior using AST-aware pattern matching.

## Tech Stack
- TypeScript (strict mode, ES2022 target)
- Node.js >= 20 (ESM modules)
- Vitest for testing
- Commander.js for CLI
- chalk for terminal output

## Code Style
- ESM imports with `.js` extensions (e.g., `from "./types.js"`)
- Node.js builtins use `node:` prefix (e.g., `import * as fs from "node:fs"`)
- No `any` — use explicit types from `src/types.ts`
- Throw `ParseError` for validation failures
- Pass `file.language` to `scanContent()` for AST-aware scanning

## Architecture
- `src/types.ts` — all TypeScript interfaces (start here)
- `src/rules/` — verification rules implementing the `Rule` interface
- `src/ast/` — context-aware code analysis (strips comments/strings)
- `src/integrations/` — external scanner adapters (Cisco, Aguara)
- `tests/` — Vitest tests mirroring src/ structure

## Key Patterns
- Rules: implement `Rule` interface from types.ts, register in `rules/index.ts`
- AST scanning: use `scanContent(content, patterns, language)` — 3rd param enables context-aware mode
- CLI commands: add via `program.command(...)` in `cli.ts`
- Integrations: follow adapter pattern in `integrations/cisco.ts`

## Testing
- Run: `npm test` or `npx vitest run`
- Use `makeSkill()` and `baseTrust()` helpers in test files
- Every new rule needs tests in `tests/rules.test.ts`
- E2E tests use `examples/trusted-skill` and `examples/untrusted-skill`

## Important Files
- `src/types.ts` — data model (TrustDeclaration, ParsedSkill, Rule, Finding, etc.)
- `src/rules/utils.ts` — core scanning utilities (scanContent, scanFiles)
- `src/ast/context.ts` — comment/string stripping state machine
- `src/verifier.ts` — orchestrates rules and computes trust level
- `TRUST-SPEC.md` — formal specification of the trust declaration schema

## Don'ts
- Don't add heavy dependencies (no tree-sitter, no babel)
- Don't use CommonJS — project is ESM only
- Don't skip the `.js` extension in relative imports
- Don't scan string literals for network/shell/env rules (use AST-aware scanning)
- Don't modify `src/types.ts` without updating dependent code
